January 21, 2016

The merger that eventually happened

In 2012, the largest ISP and cellphone carrier merged.


  • The ISP provided hardwired Internet access, TV and phone services.
  • The cellphone carrier provided regular services and mobile internet (USB modem).
  • At the end of 2011 two telecom giants in Colombia seemed to cozy with one another.
  • In February 2012 they started releasing communications, reassuring the people and the regulators. In those communications they were adamant about their unwillingness to merge. After all, they said they were doing great separate.
  • A couple months later they were talking about operating separately after the same brand. By the end of the summer they were referring to the move as merger, but it was to late for regulators.

Effects of the merger

One quarter after the merger there were signs of an increase in download speed and mobile internet traffic. It seemed as if, at least this tow dimensions of the overall provision of services had improved.

From here on I focus on the impact on the ISP side of the merger. Namely the impact on download speeds. I still don't have detailed data on cellphone services.

If one worries about mean speed increasing because slower internet plans were retired, here's the same exercise for the median speed in the markets. It shows that the median speed increase even more.

Average effect of the merger

I estimate

\[ y_{ct} = \alpha_0 + \xi_c + \alpha_1 AFTER_t + \alpha_2 MERGER_c + \alpha_3 AFTER_t \times MERGER_c + \varepsilon_{ct} \]

  • \(y_{ct}\): median download speed (or median price) in city \(c\) during quarter \(t\)
  • \(\xi_c\): city fixed effects
  • \(AFTER_t\): indicator for quarters after the merger
  • \(MERGER_c\): indicator for cities where the merged firm operates
  • A linear time trend is also included.

\(\alpha_3\) captures the effect of the merger on median speeds in cities where the merger took place, relative to those cities that did not experience it.

Here I regress a measure of speed at city level (mean or median) on indicator for the city having experienced the merger or not and an indicator for quarter after the event. The parameter associated with the interaction term should capture the effect of the merger.

Effect of the merger on rivals

To capture the effect of the merger on the outsiders I estimate the following equation: \[ y_{fct} = \mu + \gamma_1 FACES\_MERGER_j + \gamma_2 AFTER_t + \gamma_3 FACES\_MERGER_j \times AFTER_t +\\ \delta_{st} + \alpha_j + \varepsilon_{jct} \]

  • \(y_{jct}\): a measure of download speed for firm \(f\) in city \(c\) during quarter \(t\)
  • \(FACES\_MERGER_f\): an indicator for firms that compete with the merging firm.
  • \(AFTER_t\): indicator for quarters after the merger.
  • \(\delta_{st}\) : state-quarter fixed effects.

\(\gamma_3\) captures the effect of the merger on speeds offered by firms competing with the merged entity.

The standard errors are clustered at city/quarter level.

Similarly I compare firms that faced the merger in their market to other similar firms in markets where the merger didn't take place.

Effect of merger on merged firms

To capture the effect of the merger on the merged companies I estimate the following equation:

\[ y_{jct} = \mu + \phi_1 COLTEL_j + \phi_2 TELMEX_j + \phi_3 AFTER_t +\\ \gamma_2 TELMEX_j \times AFTER_t + \delta_{st} + \alpha_j + \varepsilon_{jct} \]

  • \(y\) is alternatively download speed or the price.
  • indexes are: \(j\) firms; \(c\) identifies cities; \(t\) identifies quarters.
  • Standard errors are clustered at city/quarter/firm level.

The \(\gamma\)s capture the effect of the mergers on the merged entities.

Finally I try to put a number on the effect on the merged entity by comparing them to their rivals.

Effects of the merger: summary

I added covariates and separately assess the effect of the merger

  1. Markets affected are compared to market unaffected (average effect)
  2. Rivals of the merged entity are compared to similar firms in cities where the merging firms were not present.
  3. The merged firm is compared to its rivals.

Summary of results:

  • The merged increased speeds (1.2 Mbps).
  • Rivals increased medians speeds (.5 Mbps) but reduced their maxima.
  • Median speed in cities were the merger happened increased (.6 Mbps).

Why would speeds increase after the merger?

Synergies between mobile and land-line networks

  • An engineer denied it categorically.

Facility upgrade

  • The change is too abrupt be caused by better hardware.
    • The increase of Base Transceiver Stations and Node Bs was the same before and after the merger.
    • There was no noticeable increase in optic fiber.

Strategical reasons:

  • Higher speeds are optimal after the merger due to externalities.
  • After the merger some profits are internalized.
  • Are mobile and hardwired services complementary?

  • The first thing that comes to mind is some "increased network effect". Having access to the wireless networks of the cellphone company allows the ISP to increase speeds. This was categorically denied by an engineer.

  • Did the firms undergo a huge investment in capacity that was contemporaneous? The change is so abrupt that seems unlikely. Also a look at their annual reports to shareholders shows that there hasn't been a change in the rate of investment.

  • Only strategical reasons are left. The increase in speeds reveals that higher speeds are more profitable after the merger. This would be the case in the presence of externalities. The merger internalizes profits.

  • This explanation requires the services provided by the merging parties to be complementary.

Testing for complementarities

Gentzkow (2007)

  • 2 goods \(A\) and \(B\) and consumers choose at most one unit of each.
  • The prices of the goods are \(p_A\) and \(p_B\).
  • \(\left[ \begin{matrix} \nu_A \\ \nu_B \\ \end{matrix} \right] \sim F(\mathbb{\nu})\)
  • Define \(\Gamma = (u'_{AB}-u'_B)-(u'_A-u'_0)\).

Normalizing each utility by \(u'_0\) we can write: \[u_0=0\] \[u_A=\delta_A - \alpha p_A + \nu_A\] \[u_B=\delta_B - \alpha p_B + \nu_B\] \[u_{AB}=u_A + u_B + \Gamma\]

The \(u'\)s are the baseline utilities. \(\Gamma\) would be utility added by A when B is being consumed. \(\delta\)s are mean utilities. Nus are the unobserved attributes.

Testing for complementarities

Choice probabilities

Let \(F(\mathbf{u})\) be the distribution of \(\mathbf{u}=(u_A,u_B,u_{AB})\) implied by the previous assumptions. Then the choice probabilities for utility-maximizing consumers will be:

\[q_A = \int_u I(u_A \ge 0)I(u_A \ge u_B)I(u_A \ge u_{AB})dF(\mathbf{u})\] \[q_B =\int_u I(u_B \ge 0)I(u_B\ge u_A)I(u_B \ge u_{AB})dF(\mathbf{u})\] \[q_{AB} =\int_u I(u_{AB} \ge 0)I(u_{AB}\ge u_A)I(u_{AB} \ge u_B)dF(\mathbf{u})\]

Let \(Q_A = q_A+q_{AB}\) and \(Q_B = q_B + q_{AB}\).

Definition: A and B are complements if \(\frac{\partial Q_A}{\partial p_B} <0\), susbtitutes if\(\frac{\partial Q_A}{\partial p_B} >0\) and independent if \(\frac{\partial Q_A}{\partial p_B} = 0\).

  • If F is the distribution of such a draw, as implied by the previous assumptions, and if consumers are utility maximizers, the choice probabilities are given by:

  • The magnitude of interest, though, will be the total amount of A and B and how they relate to each other prices.

  • Now one can show that there is in fact a relation between the \(\Gamma\) sign and the pattern substitution.

  • I think \(\Gamma\) should be enough to define complementarity.

Substitution patterns: \(\uparrow p_B\) and \(\Gamma = 0\)


  • marginal consumers like \(m\) will substitute \(AB\) for \(A\),
    • \(\uparrow q_A = \downarrow q_{AB}\) and \(Q_A\) remains unchanged.
  • marginal consumers like \(n\) have no impact on \(Q_A\)
  • Hence \(\Gamma = 0\) implies \(\frac{\partial Q_A}{\partial p_B}=0\) (goods are independent)
The first thing to notice is that an increase in \(p_B\) is equivalent to shifting probability mass downward.

Substitution patterns: \(\uparrow p_B\) and \(\Gamma > 0\)


  • marginal consumers like \(m\) will substitute \(AB\) for \(A\)
    • \(\uparrow q_A = \downarrow q_{AB}\)
  • marginal consumers like \(o\) will substitute \(AB\) for neither good
    • \(\downarrow q_A\) and overall \(\downarrow Q_A\)
  • Hence \(\Gamma > 0\) implies \(\frac{\partial Q_A}{\partial p_B}<0\) (goods are complements)
When \(\Gamma\) is positive it is possible to see some consumption of both A and B even for negative values of \(u_A\) and \(u_B\) and that's why this triangle appears.

Substitution patterns: \(\uparrow p_B\) and \(\Gamma < 0\)


  • marginal consumers like \(m\) will substitute \(AB\) for \(A\),
    • \(\uparrow q_A = \downarrow q_{AB}\)
  • marginal consumers like \(o\) will substitute \(B\) for \(A\)
    • \(\uparrow q_A\) and overall \(\uparrow Q_A\)
  • Hence \(\Gamma < 0\) implies \(\frac{\partial Q_A}{\partial p_B}>0\) (goods are substitutes)

Now, with negative \(\Gamma\) only for large enough values of \(u_A\) and \(u_B\) would consumer demand both. that is why the set of potential bundles is reduced.

Extension: more than 2 goods

Problem: bundles of 3 or more goods

  • The definition of complements is based on pairs.
  • Take the bundle (A,B,C). What if A and B are complements but B and c are substitutes?

Solution: With some notation bundles of any size can be expressed in terms of the pairs that can be formed with its components

  • (A,B,C) contains pairs AB, AC, BC.
  • For pairs, defining substitution patterns is straightforward.

  • Even if A,B and C are complements to each other complementarity between 3 thinks is tricky. What would be the derivative definition?

  • In the end having larger bundles only add more information. I still observe pairs where complementarity is trivially defined, but in addition I observe bundles of 3, 4 and 5 goods.

5 goods

With 5 goods (internet, mobile internet, phone, long distance and TV), consumers can choose up to 32 "bundles" (including the outside good):

  • Let \(j \in \{0,1,2...,31\}\) be the set of all possible bundles, \(h \in \{1,2,3,4,5\}\) are the singletons and \(r \in \{6,7...,15\}\) are the pairs.

  • Now a bundle containing more than two goods can be described via the pairs in it (example)

The utility of an individual \(i\) that consumes bundle \(j\) during quarter \(t\) in city \(c\) is given by

  • \(u_{ijct}=\nu_{ijct}\) if \(j=0\)

  • \(u_{ijct}=\sum_{h \in j} \delta_{hct}+ \sum_{r \in j}\Gamma_r + \epsilon_{jct}+\nu_{ijct}\) if \(j >0\)
    • where \(\delta_{hct}=\alpha price_{hct}+ x_{hct} \beta\) if \(j >0\) and \(\Gamma_r = 0\) for singletons.

Assuming that the \(\nu\)'s are distributed "extreme value", one can obtain the parameters by simple OLS on

\[log(s_{jct})-log(s_{0c}) =\sum_{h \in j} \delta_{hct}+ \sum_{r \in j}\Gamma_r + \epsilon_{jct} \]

Here the notation get a little trickier. And if there are better ways I welcome any advice. I just adapted Gentzkow's notation to my extension. Even he at some points talks about "abuse of notation".

Estimating gammas

The equation I estimate is

\[log(s_{jfct})-log(s_{0ct}) = \alpha price_{jfct} + X_{jfct}\beta + \mu_c + \mu_f + \sum_{r \in j}\Gamma_r + \epsilon_{jfct}\]

  • \(s_{jfct}\) is the share of bundle \(j\) sold by firm \(f\) in city \(c\) during quarter \(t\)
  • \(X_{jfct}\) are characteristics describing the bundle: download speed and number of channels.
  • \(price_{jfct}\) is the sum of the prices of the components of bundle \(j\)
  • \(\mu_c\) and \(\mu_f\) are city and firm fixed effects.
  • \(\Gamma_r\) are the interaction terms for each pair \(r\) that can be formed with the goods in bundle \(j\).
  • \(\epsilon_{jfct}\) is likely to be correlated with the prices.
    • I observe number of channels included but not which channels. More expensive bundles include HBO while cheaper ones don't.
  • price is instrumented with the average price of the same bundle in other markets.
    • the cost of providing a given bundle should be correlated across markets. The prices of other markets don't enter the utility of the bundle in a given market.

Conclusions

  • The merger increased the speeds without a proportional effect in prices.
    • The merged firm increased speeds more than its rivals.
  • The increase in speeds is motivated by profits that are internalized ex post.
    • I find evidence that mobile Internet (Comcel) is a complementary to hardwired Internet and TV (Telmex).
  • The benefit of the subsidies to broadband that started in 2012 are likely to be underrated
    • Given the complementarities found it is likely that mobile internet access also increased as a result (as well as phone, and TV)
  • Just like divestiture, investment in complements could dampen the negative effects of mergers.

Removing the ability to exert price discrimination

Strata and price discrimination in Colombia: basics

Small areas are labeled with a number from 1 to 6 (stratum) based on the quality of buildings and its surroundings characteristics.

  • Main uses:
    • cross-subsidize public utilities,
    • differential property tax rates,
    • focalize assistance programs.

Strata have been around for over 40 years.

Strata: unintended consequences


Strata: controversies

  • Lower strata have become a stigma.
    • May harm chance of getting a job.
    • People tend not mingle inter-strata.
  • Obstacle for households experiencing temporary bad shocks.
  • Keep households doing well in assistance programs.

For these reasons there is an initiative to get rid of them.

Strata: 3rd degree price discrimination

Because of its high correlation with income and because they can't be transferred, strata are perfect instruments for price discrimination.

Strata: 3rd degree price discrimination

Strata: 3rd degree price discrimination

The question is how will this firms set prices when they are not able to distinguish among stratum?

(3rd-degree) Price discrimination in Oligopoly

How would oligopolistic firms engaged in third-degree price discrimination respond if they lose the ability to discriminate?

Symmetric oligopoly (Holmes ,1989)

  • lower price in strong markets and increases price in weak markets.
  • output falls in the strong market and rises in the weak market.

Differentiated goods oligopoly (Corts, 1998; Armstrong and Vickers, 2001)

  • Higher prices to all consumers.
  • In some cases welfare is lower when price discrimination is permitted

how to go about it?

  • Leslie (2004) price discrimination in Broadway (Monopoly)

Demand Estimation

  • \(u_{ij}=x_j\beta + \alpha price_j + \xi_j + \varepsilon_{ij}\)

Pricing

  • \(mc_j = \omega_j \ gamma + \nu_j\)
    • \(\omega_j\) and \(\nu_j\) are observable and unobservable characteristics respectively.
    • Constant marginal cost seems reasonable in the context of cable TV and Internet.
  • \(\pi_f = \sum_{k = 1}^F \sum_{s=1}^S(p_{ks}-mc_k)q_{ks}\)
    • \(p_{ks}\) and \(q_{ks}\) are the price and quantity of good \(k\) in stratum \(s\).
  • Use first-order conditions (firms compete only through prices and within segments) to get pricing equations.
